[There are a number of lessons to be learnt from this, starting with the
NMVMA running a refresher course on the gross lesions associated with
livestock anthrax and the proper disposal of affected carcasses. The latter
should always be by incineration, preferably on site, and not burial with
or without quicklime ... the function of the latter has always escaped me
but I presume it involves a chemical 'incineration' as well as folk
memories of burying executed murderers in prison yards. Placing 1,500 lbs.
15 feet above the buried carcass, vide supra, can only increase the amount
of calcium in the soil and increase the pH, both factors associated with
extended spore persistence. In our experience, spores have a slight
positive buoyancy in nature and therefore tend to float upwards when the
soil is wet, especially when the water is full of minerals. Having
signposted the site, I do hope that the authorities will take note of any
future unlicensed excavations, potentially by folk wishing to acquire
private cultures.
Lastly, a serious problem is highlighted by this incident ... the delay
between taking samples and obtaining laboratory confirmation. Depending on
a necropsy significantly increases the potential environmental
contamination, if incineration and site control is not initiated quickly.
Fixing, staining, and reading blood smears carcass-side is not something
that most vets are capable of these days, if only because it is a rare vet
with a microscope and capsular stain in his/her pickup. We need a reliable
field-diagnostic kit, such as an ELISA dipstick test. - Mod.MHJ
